<p><b>Magic</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Performing_art" title="Performing art" class="mw-redirect">performing art</a> that <a href="/wiki/Entertain" title="Entertain" class="mw-redirect">entertains</a> an <a href="/wiki/Audience" title="Audience">audience</a> by creating <a href="/wiki/Illusion" title="Illusion">illusions</a> of seemingly impossible<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> or <a href="/wiki/Supernatural" title="Supernatural">supernatural</a><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> feats, using purely natural means. These feats are called <i>magic tricks</i>, <i>effects</i> or <i>illusions</i>.</p>
<p>One who performs such illusions is called a <i>magician</i>. Some performers may also be referred to by names reflecting the type of magical effects they present, such as <a href="/wiki/Sleight_of_hand" title="Sleight of hand">prestidigitators</a>, <a href="/wiki/Conjuration#Contemporary_references" title="Conjuration">conjurors</a>, illusionists, <a href="/wiki/Mentalism" title="Mentalism">mentalists</a>, <a href="/wiki/Escapology" title="Escapology">escape artists</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Ventriloquism" title="Ventriloquism">ventriloquists</a>.</p>
<table id="toc" class="toc" summary="Contents">
